        option: [`Alveolar hyaline membranes`, `Pulmonary arteriolosclerosis`, `Interstitial fibrosis`,`Lymphocytic infiltrates`,`Respiratory bronchiolar destruction`],
        optionFeedback: [`Sepsis is the most common cause of acute lung injury and acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), in which pulmonary endothelial damage, often mediated by activated leukocytes, leads to pulmonary inflammation and edema that organizes into alveolar hyaline membranes composed of fibrin and cellular debris. Ventilation-perfusion mismatch refers to continued perfusion of poorly aerated areas. It occurs due to thickening of the interstitium and the presence of intraalveolar edema fluid and hyaline membranes. `,`Pulmonary arteriosclerosis usually occurs secondary to longstanding pulmonary hypertension. `,`Interstitial fibrosis could be a late feature of healed acute lung injury, but the timing is wrong for this.`,`Sepsis and lung injury are associated with innate immune cell infiltrates (neutrophils and macrophages).`,`Respiratory bronchiolar destruction is a feature of emphysema, a chronic lung disorder.`],
