        q: `After a hemicolectomy to remove a colon carcinoma, a 56-year-old man develops respiratory distress. He is intubated and receives mechanical ventilation with 100% oxygen. His hemoglobin (Hb) is 11.2g/dL (13.5–17.5 g/dL), white blood cell (WBC) count is 8,500/mm<sup>3</sup> (4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>) and PT and PTT are within reference range. Three days later, his arterial oxygen saturation decreases to 60%. A chest radiograph shows increasing opacification in all lung fields. Microscopic examination of a lung biopsy shows hyaline membranes lining distended alveolar ducts and sacs. Which of the following is the most likely mechanism underlying these morphologic changes?`,
