        q: `A 58-year-old man has gradually increasing dyspnea and a 4-kg weight loss over the past 2 years. He has smoked two packs of cigarettes per day for 20 years, but not for the past year. Physical examination shows an increase in the anteroposterior diameter of the chest. Auscultation of the chest shows decreased breath sounds. A chest radiograph shows bilateral hyperlucent lungs; pulmonary function tests show that FEV<sub>1</sub> is markedly decreased, but FVC (forced vital capacity) is normal, and the FEV<sub>1</sub>:FVC ratio is decreased. Which of the following is most likely to contribute to reduction in FEV<sub>1</sub>?`,
