        optionFeedback: [`Destruction of alveolar walls is a feature of emphysema, which is typically not associated with productive cough. `,`Permanent dilation of bronchi with wall destruction defines bronchiectasis, which is associated with copious sputum production. It is treated with antibiotics and does not respond to bronchodilators. `,`Interstitial pneumonia (e.g., due to viral infection) is associated with cough but little sputum production. `,`The clinical scenario is consistent with chronic bronchitis, a form of smoking-related chronic obstructive pulmonary disease associated with productive cough due to hypersecretion of mucus from bronchial glands. It often is exacerbated by infection and hyperresponsiveness of airway smooth muscle, leading to constriction of airways that is relieved by β-adrenergic agonists, as occurs in bronchial asthma. Eventually, symptoms of both chronic bronchitis and bronchial asthma may develop, a condition called asthmatic bronchitis. `,`α1-antitrypsin disease may lead to emphysema, which does not fit the clinical scenario.`],
