        optionFeedback: [`Dilation of respiratory bronchioles due to loss of elastic fibers is a feature of emphysema.`,`Inflammatory destruction of bronchial walls defines bronchiectasis. `,`Interstitial and alveolar edema with hyaline membrane formation are features of acute respiratory distress syndrome.`,`Patchy areas of consolidation with alveolar leukocytic infiltrates are features of bronchopneumonia.`,`The clinical scenario is consistent with atopic asthma complicated by acute attacks leading to “air-trapping” due to bronchoconstriction. Characteristic morphologic changes, collectively called <b>airway remodeling</b>, include thickening of the airway wall, submucosal fibrosis, increased submucosal vascularity, an increase in the size of submucosal glands, goblet cell metaplasia, and hypertrophy of bronchial smooth muscle.  `],
