        optionFeedback: [`The clinical scenario and the presence of fibrous thickening of alveolar walls seen on microscopy is consistent with idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. This disorder is more common in males, almost never appears before the age of 50 years, and is associated with inherited defects in several genes, including genes encoding telomerase, surfactant, and a particular mucin. Some antifibrosis therapies are approved for treating affected patients, but the overall outcome remains poor.  `,`Antihistaminic drugs are used for treatment of early acute phase reactions in type I hypersensitivity disorders like hay fever and urticaria.`,`Lipoxygenase antagonists are used to treat asthma, for which there is no evidence in this patient. `,`Viral infections can cause interstitial pneumonitis that usually resolves without sequelae. Infrequently, viral infections cause diffuse alveolar damage and acute respiratory distress syndrome`,`The clinical, laboratory, and pathologic findings are inconsistent with bacterial infection, and therefore broad-spectrum antibiotics are not indicated.`],
